missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-02.md:115:### 5. There is hidden prior-art overlap
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-03.md:15:This is reasonable as a scoping move, but it hides the central failure mode. The space of choices is too broad relative to the proof burden. "Stochastic Kelvin circulation," "stochastic Cauchy formula," "backward stochastic flow," and "a martingale adapted to vorticity/stretching" are not comparable objects. They live at different regularity levels, encode different information, and have different endpoint plausibility. Putting them in one menu risks wasting effort on representational variety rather than selecting the one object most likely to interact with a blowup mechanism.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-03.md:71:### 5. It risks prior-art redundancy
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/attacks/chain-03.md:73:There is a real danger that the branch rediscovers a known pattern: exact stochastic Lagrangian reformulation, elegant martingale identity, some localized expectation estimate, then no closure at critical regularity. The chain acknowledges this possibility only abstractly. It should require an explicit prior-art checkpoint early: what exact known stochastic NS representation is being surpassed, and by what candidate gain? Without that, the route may just replay an old nonclosure in new packaging.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-002/attacks/chain-01.md:30:The chain is built around reformulations: Lamb-vector, projected, vorticity, tensor/trilinear rewrites. That is a narrow slice of the space of NS-specific structure. It sidelines mechanisms that are not just rewrites of the same quadratic term, especially dynamic or geometric ones where the useful structure is produced by the flow rather than visible in a static identity.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-002/attacks/chain-01.md:45:The mission context already records that the vorticity formulation also hits the same `beta = 4/3` barrier, and that Beltrami cancellation is extremely fragile. That does not make this chain pointless, but it does mean parts of Step 2 and Step 3 are at risk of spending budget re-certifying known negatives rather than testing genuinely live candidates.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-002/attacks/chain-01.md:55:- The chain never commits to which inherited architecture supplies the "target interaction." Is it the De Giorgi truncation bottleneck, a local-energy flux term, a projected pressure term, or something else? Those are not interchangeable. A candidate that helps one may be irrelevant to another.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-002/attacks/chain-01.md:68:- "Test the standard forms first" is partly redundant with known project history. Vorticity and Lamb-vector rewrites are not unexplored territory here. If they are retested, the chain should state exactly what is new in the localized estimate, or this is repetition disguised as rigor.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-002/attacks/chain-01.md:81:- The chain waits until after a candidate "appears to improve the estimate" before asking whether the effect is just alignment. That is backwards for this mission. Given what is already known about Beltrami fragility, geometry should be built into the first evaluation, not added as a later purity test.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-002/attacks/chain-01.md:84:- The step uses near-Beltrami mainly as a fragility screen. That is fair as a guardrail, but it ignores the possibility that localized high-vorticity regions are exactly where one should expect any non-averaged NS structure to manifest.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-008/final-decider.md:39:- prior-art redundancy;
